# Global Rules

## 1. Architecture Preference
Prefer Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) over Functional Programming (FP) for backend design.

---

## 2. SOLID Principles
All code must follow SOLID principles:
- Single Responsibility Principle
- Open/Closed Principle
- Liskov Substitution Principle
- Interface Segregation Principle
- Dependency Inversion Principle

---

## 3. Test-Driven Development (TDD)

All backend code must follow the TDD Core Philosophy defined in:
rules/testing/tdd-core.mdc

---

## 4. Behavior-Driven Development (BDD)
All features must be defined using behavior-first thinking:

- Use Given / When / Then structure to describe behavior.
- Focus on observable outcomes, not internal implementation.
- Scenarios must represent user or system behavior.

---

## 5. No Untested Production Code
Production code is only valid if:

- It is covered by automated tests
- Tests verify behavior, not implementation details
- All tests pass before a feature is considered complete

---

## 6. Domain Isolation
Backend and frontend contexts must remain strictly separated unless explicitly required.

- Backend code must not depend on frontend logic
- Frontend code must not contain backend domain rules

---

## 7. TDD Behavior Constraints

TDD must be respected as a structural constraint:

- Tests must be written before implementation logic
- Implementation must not exceed the scope defined by tests
- Refactoring must not change observable behavior